===============================
= The Hefesto's LaTeX toolset =
===============================

The Hefesto's LaTeX toolset assist you and basic .dvi generation
and also genarates the pdf for you.

To start to use it you need to include the main toolset hls:

include ~/toolsets/latex/latex.hls

After you must to declare your project, telling that it uses the
latex-htool, look:

project my_next_pulitzer : toolset "latex-htool" : "mybook.tex" ;

You only too pass the name of your main .tex file to forge function.

To compile your tex:

    hefesto --forgefiles=example.hls --example-projects=my_next_pulitzer
    
If you need to pass some option to latex, use:

    hefesto --forgefiles=example.hls --example-projects=my_next_pulitzer --latex-options=youropt

It's very simple, you could create a template to be use in any latex project, look:

include ~/toolsets/latex/latex.hls

var main_tex_filename type string;

project carbonEx : toolset "latex-htool" : $main_tex_filename ;

cabonEx.prologue()
{
    var maintex type list;
    $maintex = hefesto.sys.get_option("main-tex");
    if ($maintex.count() == 0) {
        hefesto.sys.echo("ERROR: you must to indicate the main .tex file with --main-tex option.\n");
        hefesto.sys.exit(1);
    }
    $main_text_filename = $maintex.item(0);
    hefesto.sys.echo("*** You are using CarbonEx template v0.1 ***\n");
}

carbonEx.epilogue()
{
    hefesto.sys.echo("***\n");
}

To compile you tex, with this template:

    hefesto --forgefiles=cabonEx.hls --carbonEx-projects=carbonEx --main-tex=mybook.tex
    
But it's only a sugestion.

To generate the pdf from .dvi you must to pass the command option --mkpdf:

    hefesto --forgefiles=example.hls --example-projects=my_next_pulitzer --mkpdf
    
To specifies the pdf file name:

    hefesto --forgefiles=example.hls --example-projects=my_next_pulitzer --mkpdf --pdfout=T-hooooooowl.pdf
    
The latex creates some files that you maybe want to delete them keeping your directory always clean:

    hefesto --forgefiles=example.hls --example-projects=my_next_pulitzer --keepclean

The command option "--keepclean" will removes all ".log" and ".aux" from the current directory.
